"other": "alkaline vent interface; Fischer-Tropsch-type and acetyl-CoA-analog carbon fixation regime"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction and C-C coupling of reduced C1 species on Fe oxide/metal surfaces generates C2 carboxylates such as acetate.", "reasoning": "The literature-guided network requires hydrothermal reduced-carbon buildup before C3 intermediates arise; acetate is a plausible vent product from Fe mineral-mediated carbon fixation and provides a bridge from C1 reduction to C2-C3 chemistry in hydrothermal systems (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Amend & Shock, 1998; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of acetaldehyde from reduced C2 carbon", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal reduction; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated partial reduction/deoxygenation of C2 carboxylate pools yields the aldehyde acetaldehyde, a Strecker entry substrate.", "reasoning": "Acetaldehyde is a key branch-point precursor for alanine Strecker chemistry, and the report identifies hydrothermal C2 chemistry and NiS-related acetaldehyde generation as relevant to alanine synthesis; this step is included to connect reduced hydrothermal carbon pools to the experimentally supported acetaldehyde-centered surface and alkaline cyanide routes (Diederich et al., 2023; review synthesis in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on Fe minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; anoxic; H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Multi-electron mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation and C-C coupling furnish the alpha-keto acid pyruvate as a metabolism-like hub.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is the dominant hydrothermal hub in the alanine literature and the immediate precursor for high-yield reductive amination routes; the network includes direct hydrothermal pyruvate formation because the provided instructions explicitly require pyruvate synthesis on magnetite/greigite and the report frames pyruvate as a plausible vent-generated C3 hub (Barge et al., 2019; Novikov & Copley, 2013; report synthesis)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface atmospheric discharge generation of HCN", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces as photochemical/condensation supports", "aqueous": "true", "other": "volcanic plume/tidal pool rainout context; UV exposure; discharge-derived feedstock accumulation"}, "mechanism": "Energetic atmospheric chemistry and post-rainout trapping create cyanide pools that accumulate on mineral surfaces and in shallow aqueous settings.", "reasoning": "Miller-type and volcanic discharge experiments produce HCN, NH3, and carbonyls that feed Strecker chemistry; this node captures that documented atmospheric-to-surface input in a surface-compatible prebiotic pool framework (Miller, 1953; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "UV-mediated hydration of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV photochemistry in evaporitic or geothermal pools"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical conversion of cyanide-derived carbon-nitrogen species in water yields formamide-enriched pools.", "reasoning": "Formamide-rich settings are explicitly relevant to acetaldehyde-derived alanine aminonitrile and N-formyl-Ala-CN formation in the Green et al. staged-heating system; this step supplies that solvent/reactive medium from the cyanide hub (Green et al., 2023; report synthesis)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Alkaline Strecker formation of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and clay concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline cyanide/ammonium conditions; wet-dry concentration; imine formation followed by CN addition"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to give 2-aminopropanenitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical Strecker route for alanine and is directly supported by the report as the most direct small-molecule route via acetaldehyde + NH3 + CN\u2212 to Ala-CN; Diederich et al. also link hydrothermal-adjacent acetaldehyde production to alanine formation under alkaline KCN/NH4Cl conditions (Diederich et al., 2023; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013; report synthesis)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formamide staged-heating conversion of alanine aminonitrile to N-formyl-Ala-CN", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "staged heating, 300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide-rich setting; extended heating history shifts product distribution toward N-formylaminonitrile"}, "mechanism": "Formylation of alanine aminonitrile in formamide-rich media traps the nitrile as a more persistent precursor pool.", "reasoning": "Green et al. explicitly report efficient formation of Ala-CN and N-formyl-Ala-CN from acetaldehyde-derived inputs under staged heating in formamide systems, with the formylated product often becoming dominant; this reaction follows that literature directly (Green et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to DL-alanine", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "context-dependent aqueous hydrolysis; bottleneck step in aminonitrile-first pathways"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis through amide-like intermediates releases free alanine.", "reasoning": "The report emphasizes that alanine synthesis by Strecker chemistry is often best viewed as alanine-precursor synthesis followed by environmentally contingent hydrolysis; this hydrolysis step is therefore included as the critical release step from the Ala-CN reservoir (Green et al., 2023; Diederich et al., 2023; report synthesis)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of N-formyl-Ala-CN to DL-alanine", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous deprotection and nitrile hydrolysis during later pool processing"}, "mechanism": "Sequential deformylation and nitrile hydrolysis convert the protected aminonitrile pool into free alanine.", "reasoning": "Green et al. identify N-formyl-Ala-CN as a major product in formamide-rich staged-heating systems; the report notes that such protected nitrile pools plausibly feed later alanine release by hydrolysis, making this a necessary literature-grounded connection step though the exact environmental hydrolysis sequence remains partly unresolved (Green et al., 2023; report synthesis, noted bottleneck/speculative connection)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide reductive amination of pyruvate to DL-alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K (70\u00b0C)", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe(II):Fe(III)=1:1 iron oxyhydroxide precipitates", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 10; warm alkaline vent conditions; reaction completion in 48-72 h; alanine/lactate competition"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms imine/iminium-like intermediates with ammonia at mixed-valence iron surfaces; selective reduction yields alanine while a competing reduction branch yields lactate.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest hydrothermal alanine synthesis module in the literature: Barge et al. report maximum ~70% alanine with ~30% lactate at pH 10, Fe(II):Fe(III)=1:1, 70\u00b0C over 48-72 h, showing mixed-valence iron minerals strongly favor reductive amination of pyruvate under vent-like conditions (Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Ni0/H2 reductive amination of pyruvate to DL-alanine under mild aqueous conditions", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "native nickel (Ni0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K (22\u00b0C)", "pressure": "5 bar", "catalyst": "Ni nanoparticles/native metal surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 7-8; 24 h; pyruvate ca. 30 mM; representative alanine yield ~17% on Ni"}, "mechanism": "Hydrogen-activated native metal catalysis reduces pyruvate-derived imine species formed with ammonia to alanine.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. directly report pyruvate reductive amination to alanine at 22\u00b0C, pH 7-8, 5 bar H2, 24 h over Ni catalysts, with ~17% alanine, establishing a mild native-metal route complementary to warm alkaline iron mineral chemistry (Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Vent sulfide mineral reductive amination landscape producing alanine from pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-383K (25-110\u00b0C)", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "transition-metal sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "vent-gas mixtures including H2/H2S/CO2; NH4Cl present (~70 mM in alanine-focused runs); mineral-dependent yields"}, "mechanism": "Vent sulfide minerals modulate competing pyruvate sinks; under ammonium-containing vent-gas conditions, reductive amination yields alanine at mineral-dependent levels.", "reasoning": "Novikov & Copley show that pyruvate under simulated vent conditions with H2/H2S/CO2 and NH4Cl gives alanine in the presence of several sulfide minerals, with strong mineral dependence; this reaction encodes that experimentally mapped reactivity landscape rather than claiming a single dominant catalyst (Novikov & Copley, 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Ni0-catalyzed reductive amination of pyridoxal to pyridoxamine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K (80\u00b0C)", "pressure": "5 bar", "catalyst": "Ni0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 11; serpentinization-like conditions; NH3 as low as ~5 mM; conversion within hours"}, "mechanism": "Native nickel catalyzes reductive amination of pyridoxal to pyridoxamine, generating a soluble amino-transfer shuttle.", "reasoning": "Schlikker et al. directly demonstrate Ni0-catalyzed conversion of pyridoxal to pyridoxamine at pH 11, 80\u00b0C, H2 5 bar under serpentinization-like conditions, establishing the cofactor-enabled transamination module used downstream (Schlikker et al., 2024/2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "