rt efficient formation of Ala-CN and N-formyl-Ala-CN from acetaldehyde-derived inputs under staged heating, with N-formyl-Ala-CN often dominant after extended heating. This directly addresses the literature-defined bottleneck by storing alanine skeletons in protected precursor pools. (Green et al., 2023)"}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrolysis release of alanine from alanine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable, hydrolysis bottleneck", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous processing after concentration or staged heating; nitrile hydrolysis may proceed via amide intermediates"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis converts the nitrile carbon to carboxylate, releasing free alanine into solution.", "reasoning": "The review explicitly frames alanine synthesis in Strecker systems as aminonitrile-first, with hydrolysis being the environmental bottleneck for release of free amino acid. This step is therefore included as a necessary literature-grounded conversion from precursor pool to alanine. (Green et al., 2023; Diederich et al., 2023)"}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrolysis release of alanine from N-formyl-Ala-CN", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable, after staged heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "deprotection and hydrolysis in later aqueous setting; included as context-dependent release from protected precursor pool"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolysis and deformylation of N-formyl-aminonitrile release free alanine in aqueous environments.", "reasoning": "Green et al. (2023) support N-formyl-Ala-CN as a major product under prebiotic formamide heating regimes; the report explicitly interprets these species as plausible protected precursor pools for later alanine release by hydrolysis. The exact hydrolysis regime remains a gap in the literature, so this connection is included conservatively as a necessary completion step. (Green et al., 2023; review synthesis in the provided report)"}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "70\u00b0C", "pressure": "low to moderate", "catalyst": "mixed Fe(II):Fe(III) oxyhydroxide precipitates, optimal Fe(II):Fe(III)=1:1", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 10; completion over 48-72 h; alanine up to ~70% with ~30% lactate competitor"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms imine-like intermediates with ammonia and is reductively aminated on mixed-valence iron phases, while competing reduction yields lactate.", "reasoning": "Barge et al. (2019) provide the strongest quantitative hydrothermal-like route to alanine: pyruvate plus ammonia on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides at pH 10 and 70\u00b0C gives maximal alanine yield near 70%, with lactate as the main competitor. The mineral agents map the required hydrothermal mineral field while preserving the literature's mixed-valence iron logic. (Barge et al., 2019)"}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Ni0/H2 reductive amination of pyruvate under mild aqueous conditions", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "22\u00b0C", "pressure": "5 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni nanoparticles / native metal regime", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 7-8; 24 h; representative alanine yield ~17% over Ni nanoparticles"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate condenses with ammonia to an imine-like intermediate and is hydrogenatively aminated under native-metal catalysis.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) report pyruvate reductive amination with NH3 and H2 at 5 bar, 22\u00b0C, pH 7-8, giving ~17% alanine over Ni nanoparticles and higher yields over Pd. The network uses the Ni-native-metal branch because it is more prebiotically plausible than Pd, and Fe-bearing agents are included to satisfy hydrothermal mineral requirements. (Kaur et al., 2024)"}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Vent-mineral pyruvate reactivity landscape including alanine branch", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "25-110\u00b0C", "pressure": "vent-gas mixture", "catalyst": "transition-metal sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H2/H2S/CO2 gas load; ~70 mM NH4Cl in alanine-probing experiments; strongly mineral-dependent product distributions"}, "mechanism": "Transition-metal sulfide surfaces redirect pyruvate among reductive amination, reduction, thiolation, and other competing channels, with alanine and lactate among the outcomes.", "reasoning": "Novikov and Copley (2013) mapped the hydrothermal reactivity landscape of pyruvate and showed alanine formation under vent-like gas loads with sulfide minerals, but with strikingly mineral-dependent product distributions. This node captures the literature-supported redundancy of pyruvate-to-alanine routes without claiming a single optimized mineral beyond what was reported. (Novikov & Copley, 2013)"}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Ni0-catalyzed reductive amination of pyridoxal to pyridoxamine in serpentinization-like conditions", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "80\u00b0C", "pressure": "5 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 11; hours; shown to operate with as little as ~5 mM NH3"}, "mechanism": "Reductive amination of pyridoxal forms pyridoxamine, generating a soluble amino-group shuttle under serpentinization-like conditions.", "reasoning": "Schlikker et al. (2024/2025) demonstrate Ni0-catalyzed conversion of pyridoxal to pyridoxamine at pH 11, 80\u00b0C, and H2 5 bar, establishing a proto-biochemical nitrogen shuttle compatible with vent settings. This is a key literature bridge from mineral-tethered synthesis to solution transamination. (Schlikker et al., 2024/2025)"}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Pyridoxamine-mediated transamination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "20-75\u00b0C", "pressure": "1 atm to 5 bar H2-compatible setting", "catalyst": "pyridoxal/pyridoxamine with Fe3+ or Al3+ cooperativity; enhanced in Ni0 serpentinization-like systems", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 5-7.5 for metal-pyridoxal transamination benchmarks; pyruvate-to-alanine enhancement at pH 11, 80\u00b0C when pyridoxal is added in Ni0 systems"}, "mechanism": "Pyridoxamine transfers its amino group to pyruvate through Schiff-base chemistry, regenerating pyridoxal and forming alanine.", "reasoning": "Dherbassy et al. (2023) show strong metal-pyridoxal cooperativity for nonenzymatic transamination under prebiotic conditions, while Schlikker et al. (2024/2025) show that pyridoxal addition strongly increases pyruvate-to-alanine conversion in Ni0/H2 serpentinization-like systems. This reaction captures the proto-biochemical transamination branch directly identified in the literature. (Dherbassy et al., 2023; Schlikker et al., 2024/2025)"}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Circularly polarized UV photolysis and mineral-assisted enrichment of L-alanine from racemate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "far-UV circularly polarized irradiation of alanine films followed by amplification/selection; small ee only, up to ~4% optical purity reported"}, "mechanism": "Asymmetric photolysis produces a small enantiomeric excess that can be preserved or modestly amplified in subsequent physical selection cycles.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly states that direct alanine synthesis is generally racemic and that L-alanine requires a separate selection module. Circularly polarized UV irradiation of alanine films has been reported to generate up to ~4% optical purity, making this the most defensible direct L-bias module in the provided research. This step is intentionally framed as partial enrichment, not complete homochiral conversion. (Modica et al., 2015; review synthesis in the provided report)"}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Selective mineral adsorption/crystallization amplification of L-alanine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "interaction with calcite or quartz surfaces during repeated wetting, dissolution, adsorption, and crystallization cycles"}, "mechanism": "Weakly enantioselective adsorption on chiral mineral surfaces partitions alanine enantiomers and can amplify small initial L-excess generated elsewhere.", "reasoning": "Hazen et al. (2001) report selective adsorption behavior of D- and L-alanine on calcite, while later modeling suggests the energetic bias is weak (<1 kcal/mol), so this should be treated as an amplification module rather than a primary synthesis route. The reaction is included to satisfy the literature's requirement that L-alanine emergence likely needed a post-synthetic physical selection process. (Hazen et al., 2001; Asthagiri & Hazen, 2007; Joshi et al., 2021)"}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate to alanine on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides", "description": "A warm alkaline vent route in which pyruvate is converted directly to DL-alanine with high selectivity on mixed Fe(II)/Fe(I