nce >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Alanine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network follows the literature-supported conclusion that prebiotic alanine synthesis is best modeled as two converging core modules: (1) pyruvate-centered reductive amination/transamination in hydrothermal or serpentinization-like settings, and (2) acetaldehyde-centered Strecker/aminonitrile chemistry in surface or hydrothermal-adjacent alkaline systems. Because the literature shows direct synthesis is generally racemic, the network explicitly separates robust DL-alanine production from weaker but documented post-synthetic L-enrichment modules based on circularly polarized UV photolysis and enantioselective mineral adsorption. To avoid unsupported steps, upstream feedstocks are limited to species and transformations directly described in the provided research, especially acetaldehyde generation from C2H2/CO/NiS-related chemistry, pyruvate-based alanine synthesis on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides and Ni0/H2 systems, and formamide/N-formyl-aminonitrile precursor pools.\n\nMOLECULES (14 nodes):\n  - mol_001: C2H2 (acetylene) [starting]\n  - mol_002: CO (carbon monoxide) [starting]\n  - mol_003: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: HCN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_006: C3H6N2 (alanine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C4H6N2O (N-formyl-Ala-CN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H4O3 (pyruvic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H6O3 (lactic acid) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C8H11NO3 (pyridoxal) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C8H12N2O2 (pyridoxamine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H7NO2 (DL-alanine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C3H7NO2 (L-alanine) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (14 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_003 (Hydrothermal-adjacent NiS-mediated generation of acetaldehyde from acetylene and carbon monoxide) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_002, mol_005 -> mol_004 (Atmospheric/plume generation and aqueous trapping of hydrogen cyanide) [Surface]\n  - rxn_003: mol_004 -> mol_007 (Surface hydration and concentration of cyanide to formamide) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_003, mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_006 (Canonical Strecker formation of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_003, mol_007, mol_005, mol_004 -> mol_008 (Formamide-staged heating formation of N-formyl-Ala-CN from acetaldehyde-derived inputs) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_006 -> mol_013 (Hydrolysis release of alanine from alanine aminonitrile) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_007: mol_008 -> mol_013 (Hydrolysis release of alanine from N-formyl-Ala-CN) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_008: mol_009, mol_005 -> mol_013, mol_010 (Mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_009: mol_009, mol_005 -> mol_013 (Ni0/H2 reductive amination of pyruvate under mild aqueous conditions) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_010: mol_009, mol_005 -> mol_013, mol_010 (Vent-mineral pyruvate reactivity landscape including alanine branch) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_011: mol_011, mol_005 -> mol_012 (Ni0-catalyzed reductive amination of pyridoxal to pyridoxamine in serpentinization-like conditions) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_009, mol_012 -> mol_013, mol_011 (Pyridoxamine-mediated transamination of pyruvate to alanine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_013: mol_013 -> mol_014 (Circularly polarized UV photolysis and mineral-assisted enrichment of L-alanine from racemate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_014: mol_013 -> mol_014 (Selective mineral adsorption/crystallization amplification of L-alanine) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Hydrothermal pyruvate to alanine on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides (2 steps)\n  - P2: Ni0/H2 room-temperature reductive amination route (2 steps)\n  - P3: Vent sulfide mineral pyruvate landscape route (2 steps)\n  - P4: Proto-biochemical pyridoxal shuttle route (3 steps)\n  - P5: Hydrothermal-adjacent acetaldehyde Strecker route (4 steps)\n  - P6: Formamide-protected aminonitrile route (6 steps)\n  - P7: Direct surface Strecker aminonitrile hydrolysis route (4 steps)\n  - P8: Protected precursor release route from N-formyl-Ala-CN (5 steps)\n  - P9: Cross-environment hydrothermal acetaldehyde plus surface cyanide convergence (5 steps)\n  - P10: Integrated pyruvate and aminonitrile convergence to alanine pool (5 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_003, mol_004, mol_006, mol_009, mol_013\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of L\u2011Alanine\nScope and evaluation criteria\nL\u2011alanine (2\u2011aminopropanoic acid) is the simplest chiral proteinogenic amino acid, so \u201cmaking alanine\u201d and \u201cmaking enantioenriched alanine\u201d are separable problems. Most abiotic routes generate racemic alanine (D/L \u2248 1) unless an additional chiral\u2011selection or amplification process is invoked (e.g., asymmetric photochemistry or enantioselective adsorption/crystallization). This report therefore treats (i) plausible prebiotic production of \u03b1\u2011alanine (often DL), and (ii) mechanisms that could bias toward L\u2011alanine and/or amplify small initial enantiomeric excesses.\nTo keep pathways comparable across environments, the synthesis routes are organized around the dominant carbon skeleton entry points for alanine: (a) acetaldehyde \u2192 alanine via Strecker\u2011type chemistry, and (b) pyruvate (or related 2\u2011oxoacids) \u2192 alanine via reductive amination / transamination. These two nodes recur across atmospheric discharge experiments, cyanosulfidic surface networks, hydrothermal vent simulations, and mineral/metal catalysis studies. [1]\nKnown and proposed synthesis routes\nAtmospheric energy inputs and spark discharge chemistry\nThe classic demonstration that alanine can form from simple gases under energetic forcing comes from Stanley L. Miller[2] (1953, Science[3]): an electric discharge through a reducing gas mixture in contact with liquid water produced several amino acids, including \u03b1\u2011alanine (proteinogenic) and \u03b2\u2011alanine (non\u2011proteinogenic). The setup used boiling water to circulate gases and trap soluble products in the aqueous phase, with continuous discharge for roughly a week; Miller reported amino acids accumulating in the water phase and identified \u03b1\u2011alanine by paper chromatography. [4]\nThe later reanalysis of archived discharge products by Adam P. Johnson[5] and colleagues (2008, Science) showed that a \u201cvolcanic\u201d modification (steam aspiration into the spark) yielded a broader amino\u2011acid inventory and provided relative abundance ratios for alanine vs. glycine (Table S1). In that work, alanine\u2019s molar amount relative to glycine (glycine = 1) was reported as 2.7\u00d710\u207b\u00b2 for one apparatus configuration and as high as 0.9\u20131.4 in others, illustrating that alanine abundance is highly sensitive to discharge configuration and gas/water handling. [6]\nA key relevance point: discharge/atmospheric routes naturally produce intermediates used by Strecker chemistry (HCN, aldehydes/ketones, NH\u2083), so the downstream formation of \u03b1\u2011amino acids can be interpreted as an in situ Strecker\u2011like network operating in the aqueous trap. This conceptual link\u2014energetic atmospheric production of HCN/aldehydes followed by aqueous conversion to amino acids\u2014underpins many \u201cprebiotic soup\u201d models. [7]\nA sulfur\u2011enriched volcanic\u2011plume variant was demonstrated in archived samples analyzed by Ernest T. Parker[8] et al. (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America[9]): spark discharge with H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 produced 23 amino acids and 4 amines, and importantly, alanine was reported racemic within error (D/L = 1 \u00b1 10%) among the more abundant chiral products\u2014consistent with an abiotic origin (and arguing against simple terrestrial contamination). [10]\nStrecker\u2011type chemistry from aldehydes, cyanide, and ammonia\nFor alanine specifically, the Strecker target is acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO): acetaldehyde + NH\u2083 + CN\u207b \u2192 2\u2011aminopropionitrile (alanine aminonitrile; \u201cAla\u2011CN\u201d), then hydrolysis \u2192 alanine. This is the most direct \u201csmall\u2011molecule\u201d entry route because acetaldehyde, ammonia, and cyanide are all plausible prebiotic species derived from atmospheric/photochemical/impact processes. [11]\nModern prebiotic literature emphasizes that aminonitriles are often more robust than free amino acids, and that formylation (e.g., in formamide\u2011rich settings) can stabilize or re\u2011route nitrile chemistry. In a formamide system, Neil J. Green[12] et al. (2023, Journal of the American Chemical Society[13]) report efficient formation of Ala\u2011CN and N\u2011formyl\u2011Ala\u2011CN from acetaldehyde\u2011derived inputs under staged heating. For the methyl side chain case (alanine skeleton), their Table 3/4 data show substantial conversion into aminonitrile and/or N\u2011formylaminonitrile depending on whether ammonia is supplied and how thermal history is applied (with N\u2011formyl\u2011Ala\u2011CN becoming dominant after extended heating sequences). [14]\nA complementary hydrothermal\u2011adjacent route couples acetylene/CO chemistry to acetaldehyde generation and then Strecker steps. Philipp Diederich[15] et al. (2023, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America[9]) report conditions under which acetaldehyde is generated from C\u2082H\u2082/CO/NiS\u2011related chemistry and\u2014when KCN and NH\u2084Cl are introduced under alkaline conditions\u2014alanine forms, with a reported 180 \u00b5M alanine corresponding to an estimated 0.02% yield (based on NH\u2084Cl) after 7 days in the specific setup they highlight. [16]\nBecause early\u2011Earth cyanide availability is debated, cyanide reservoir concepts are frequently invoked. Marta Ruiz-Bermejo[17] et al. (2013, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres[18]) discuss ferrocyanides as potential cyanide\u2011bearing intermediates relevant to \u03b1\u2011amino acid synthesis and cite older experimental Strecker work reporting high alanine yields (~55%) under laboratory Strecker conditions using NaCN and NH\u2084Cl (not itself a prebiotic simulation, but a key yield benchmark for the intrinsic chemistry). [19]\nHydrothermal / vent\u2011analog routes via reductive amination of pyruvate\nA second major entry point is pyruvate (CH\u2083\u2011CO\u2011COO\u207b), which becomes alanine by reductive amination (net: pyruvate + NH\u2083 + [reducing equivalents] \u2192 alanine). This approach is central to \u201cmetabolism\u2011first\u201d scenarios because pyruvate is both a universal metabolic hub and plausibly produced in some hydrothermal/metal systems. [20]\nA particularly quantitative demonstration is Laura M. Barge[21] et al. (2019, PNAS): mixed\u2011valence iron oxyhydroxide precipitates (variable Fe(II):Fe(III)) drive pyruvate toward alanine or lactate depending on pH and redox state. They report a maximum alanine yield ~70% (with ~30% lactate) at pH 10, Fe(II):Fe(III) = 1:1, and 70\u202f\u00b0C; kinetics indicate completion on the order of 48\u201372 h under \u201cwarm alkaline vent\u201d conditions. Purely ferrous hydroxide favored lactate, while ferric hydroxides did not yield detectable reaction products, highlighting that partial oxidation state (i.e., mixed Fe(II)/Fe(III)) is critical for alanine formation in that system. [22]\nA complementary track uses H\u2082 as reductant on native metals/meteorites. Harpreet Kaur[23] et al. (2024, Chem[24]; open via PubMed Central[25]) report reductive amination of multiple 2\u2011oxoacids with NH\u2083 and H\u2082 over various catalysts at mild conditions. For pyruvate \u2192 alanine specifically, they report (representative conditions) 30 mM pyruvate, pH 7\u20138, 22\u202f\u00b0C, 24 h with H\u2082 at 5 bar, yielding ~44% alanine over Pd nanoparticles and ~17% alanine over Ni nanoparticles (both expressed as yield relative to ammonia consumption in the cited table excerpt). [26]\nHydrothermal vent mineralogy can also steer pyruvate among competing outcomes. Yehor Novikov[27] and Shelley D. Copley[28] (2013, PNAS) mapped pyruvate\u2019s \u201creactivity landscape\u201d with several transition\u2011metal sulfide minerals under vent\u2011fluid\u2011like gas loads and showed that reductive amination to alanine occurs, but at levels that vary strongly with the mineral present and with H\u2082S/H\u2082/NH\u2084Cl conditions. Their experiments used ~70 mM NH\u2084Cl in some runs \u201cto examine the potential for reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine,\u201d and they emphasize that product distributions reflect competition among multiple mineral\u2011accelerated pathways. [29]\nProto\u2011biochemical assembly via pyridoxal chemistry and transamination\nBeyond net \u201cbuilding from scratch,\u201d alanine can also be assembled by transamination (pyruvate + amino donor \u21c4 alanine + keto\u2011acid), which is central to modern biochemistry and could plausibly operate pre\u2011enzymatically if pyridoxal (vitamin\u2011B\u2086 scaffold) and metal ions or small peptides provide catalysis.\nTwo recent studies are especially relevant:\n\u2022\tQuentin Dherbassy[30] et al. (2023, Journal of the American Chemical Society; accessible summary via PubMed) show strong metal\u2013pyridoxal cooperativity in nonenzymatic transamination under prebiotically relevant ranges (20\u201375\u202f\u00b0C, pH 5\u20137.5). In their reported benchmarks, Fe\u00b3\u207a\u2013pyridoxal at 75\u202f\u00b0C and 7.5 mol% loading is ~90\u00d7 faster than pyridoxal alone and ~174\u00d7 faster than Fe\u00b3\u207a alone for transamination; Al\u00b3\u207a\u2013pyridoxal shows similar cooperative acceleration. [31]\n\u2022\tManon L. Schlikker[32] et al. (2025 issue; e\u2011published 2024, FEBS Journal[33]; open via PubMed Central) demonstrate a hybrid nitrogen shuttle in serpentinization\u2011like conditions: Ni\u2070 catalyzes reductive amination of pyridoxal \u2192 pyridoxamine with as little as ~5 mM NH\u2083 and H\u2082 (5 bar) at pH 11, 80\u202f\u00b0C within hours, and pyridoxal addition strongly increases pyruvate \u2192 alanine conversion under the same vent\u2011like conditions. Quantitatively, at pH 11 and 80\u202f\u00b0C for 18 h, they report 7.6% conversion of pyruvate to alanine without pyridoxal vs 34% with pyridoxal (a 4.4\u00d7 increase), with higher\u2011temperature cases reaching up to ~48% conversion. [34]\nThese proto\u2011biochemical routes do not inherently specify L vs D alanine; they primarily address network plausibility (how amino transfer chemistry becomes soluble and catalytic before enzymes) and provide a bridge between mineral\u2011tethered synthesis and solution networks. [35]\nExtraterrestrial ice photochemistry and delivery\nAlanine is also produced in UV\u2011processed icy mixtures meant to mimic interstellar or outer\u2011solar\u2011system ices, typically detected after aqueous workup/hydrolysis of complex organic residues. Guillermo M. Mu\u00f1oz Caro[36] et al. (2002, Nature[37]) is a widely cited example showing amino acid production, including alanine, from UV irradiation of \u201cdirty ice\u201d analogs. [38]\nCritically for L\u2011alanine, asymmetric photochemistry has been explored: exposure of racemic alanine films to far\u2011UV circularly polarized synchrotron radiation can yield measurable optical purity. For example, an Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres study reports optical purities up to ~4% for alanine as a function of CPL helicity and wavelength selection. [39]\nKey intermediates and precursor networks\nAlanine production routes repeatedly pass through a small set of intermediates that act as branch points in broader prebiotic networks:\nAcetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO) is the key C\u2083 \u201cstarter\u201d for Strecker alanine. It can itself be produced by multiple prebiotic processes: atmospheric discharge/radical chemistry, photochemical oxidation/reduction sequences, hydrothermal reactions involving C\u2082 substrates, or from smaller carbonyls through carbon\u2011chain growth. In hydrothermal catalysis contexts, acetaldehyde\u2019s formation and stabilization compete with hydration, aldolization, and further oxidation/reduction reactions, making its steady\u2011state availability a major uncertainty. [40]\nAla\u2011CN (2\u2011aminopropionitrile) is the Strecker\u2011type immediate precursor. It branches into: * hydrolysis \u2192 alanine (via amide intermediate), * N\u2011formylation \u2192 N\u2011formyl\u2011Ala\u2011CN (potentially stabilizing or re\u2011directing downstream chemistry in formamide systems), * side reactions producing amino alcohols or imine chemistry, depending on water activity and pH. [41]\nPyruvate (CH\u2083\u2011CO\u2011COO\u207b) is the key \u201cmetabolism\u2011like\u201d C\u2083 hub. It branches into: * reductive amination \u2192 alanine, * reduction \u2192 lactate (dominant competitor in many mineral and metal systems), * reduction/deoxygenation \u2192 propionate under some sulfide\u2011mineral conditions, * aldol condensation products (C\u2086) that could connect into sugar/energy metabolism analogs. [42]\nImine/Schiff\u2011base intermediates unify Strecker, reductive amination, and transamination: * Strecker: acetaldehyde + NH\u2083 \u21c4 imine; CN\u207b addition \u2192 aminonitrile. * Reductive amination: pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u21c4 imine/imine\u2011like species; reduction \u2192 amino acid. * Transamination: pyridoxal/pyridoxamine\u2011dependent Schiff bases mediate amino transfer and regenerate the cofactor scaffold. [43]\nFrom a network\u2011design perspective, two practical takeaways follow from the literature above: 1) pyruvate and acetaldehyde are not \u201csingle\u2011pathway\u201d precursors; each sits at a dense junction where mineralogy/pH/redox decide which branch dominates, and 2) nitriles and imines are \u201ccontrol knobs\u201d for robustness: they can stabilize nitrogen incorporation (nitriles) or catalyze redistribution of amino groups (Schiff bases), but can also trap material in hard\u2011to\u2011hydrolyze pools depending on conditions. [44]\nReaction mechanisms and conditions\nSpark\u2011discharge pathways\nIn Miller\u2011type discharge systems, the mechanistic picture is a coupled gas\u2011phase radical network plus aqueous\u2011phase capture and secondary reactions. The empirical constraints from the original report are:\n\u2022\tWater reservoir heated/boiled; discharge run continuously ~1 week.\n\u2022\tReduced gases (H\u2082, CH\u2084, NH\u2083) under sub\u2011atmospheric pressure in a glass apparatus.\n\u2022\tIdentification of glycine and \u03b1\u2011alanine among the amino acids accumulated in water phase, with \u201cmilligram\u2011range\u201d total amino\u2011acid yield (as reported qualitatively). [4]\nThe reanalysis of archived \u201cvolcanic apparatus\u201d samples indicates that alanine abundance can be near\u2011glycine in some discharge geometries (alanine/glycine molar ratio ~0.9\u20131.4), implying that discharge configuration and water cycling can shift selectivity dramatically. [45]\nSulfur\u2011containing discharge experiments demonstrate that adding H\u2082S/CO\u2082 shifts the product set and that abundant chiral amino acids (including alanine) can be racemic, consistent with in\u2011apparatus synthesis rather than contamination. [10]\nStrecker and aminonitrile\u2011first pathways\nThe canonical Strecker mechanism (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 amino acid) is chemically straightforward, but prebiotic plausibility is dominated by conditions:\n\u2022\tpH control: imine formation and cyanide speciation depend on pH; hydrolysis of nitriles to acids typically requires water and can be slow at neutral pH without catalysis.\n\u2022\tWater activity: wet\u2013dry cycles or eutectic concentration can accelerate dehydration (imine formation) and concentrate reactants, but also risk polymerization/tarring.\nTwo experimentally grounded prebiotic\u2011leaning implementations are illustrative:\n1) In alkaline systems where acetaldehyde is available, addition of cyanide and ammonium can yield alanine at low but measurable levels (reported 180 \u00b5M alanine; 0.02% yield basis NH\u2084Cl over 7 days in the cited configuration). [16]\n2) In formamide\u2011rich systems, aldehyde\u2011derived aminonitriles can be trapped as N\u2011formylaminonitriles, with staged heating shifting product distributions strongly toward formylated species; for alanine\u2011skeleton (R = Me) cases, reported conversions show that thermal history can drive aminonitrile \u2194 N\u2011formylaminonitrile partitioning to high levels. [14]\nFrom a design standpoint, these aminonitrile\u2011first routes emphasize that \u201calanine synthesis\u201d may be better cast as \u201calanine\u2011precursor synthesis + context\u2011dependent hydrolysis,\u201d because the hydrolysis step is often the environmental bottleneck. [46]\nReductive amination of pyruvate in iron mineral systems\nThe iron\u2011oxyhydroxide gradient system of Barge et al. provides unusually explicit parameter dependence:\n\u2022\tPrecipitate redox state: Fe(II):Fe(III) fraction from 0 to 100% changes whether pyruvate reacts and whether alanine vs lactate dominates.\n\u2022\tpH range tested: roughly pH 5 to 11.\n\u2022\tTemperature range: 25 to 80\u202f\u00b0C.\n\u2022\tTimecourse: typically followed out to 72 h, with alanine often first appearing at ~24 h when it forms; completion in ~48\u201372 h under productive conditions.\n\u2022\tBest\u2011case selectivity: ~70% alanine (and ~30% lactate) at pH 10, Fe(II):Fe(III)=1:1, and 70\u202f\u00b0C. [47]\nMechanistically, their scheme is consistent with two competing reduction pathways from pyruvate: reduction to lactate vs reductive amination to alanine. Their results imply that mixed\u2011valence iron hydroxides supply the right balance of redox reactivity to favor C\u2013N incorporation rather than simple carbonyl reduction under alkaline conditions. [48]\nReductive amination over native metals and meteoritic catalysts in water\nThe Ni/Pd/meteorite catalysis results (Kaur et al.) constrain a distinct regime:\n\u2022\tMild aqueous pH (7\u20138), room temperature (22\u202f\u00b0C), relatively short time (24 h).\n\u2022\tH\u2082 supply at ~5 bar.\n\u2022\tPyruvate present at tens of millimolar.\n\u2022\tAlanine yields ranging from ~17% (Ni) to ~44% (Pd) in the cited comparison. [26]\nIn parallel, Schlikker et al. show that under strongly alkaline serpentinization\u2011like conditions (pH 11, 80\u2013100\u202f\u00b0C), pyridoxal can suppress competing lactate formation and substantially increase alanine yield from pyruvate on Ni\u2070\u2014suggesting that combining native metal catalysis with soluble cofactor scaffolds can shift selectivity and potentially create a more \u201cdiffusible\u201d protometabolic nitrogen chemistry. [34]\nThermodynamic context for hydrothermal alanine synthesis\nThermodynamic analyses support the plausibility that amino\u2011acid synthesis can be energetically favored in certain hydrothermal mixtures. John P. Amend[49] and Everett L. Shock[50] (1998, Science; summary via NASA NTRS) report that thermodynamic calculations find amino\u2011acid synthesis more favorable in hot (100\u202f\u00b0C), moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions than in cold, oxidized seawater, with multiple amino acids exergonic in the hot mixture. [51]\nA commonly cited specific value from this work is that net alanine synthesis in a 100\u202f\u00b0C mixed hydrothermal solution can be exergonic (e.g., reported as releasing ~12.12 kJ/mol under a specified mixed\u2011fluid scenario). [52]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces\nIron oxides/oxyhydroxides and mixed\u2011valence phases\nThe Barge et al. system uses iron oxyhydroxide precipitates designed to mimic early\u2011Earth mildly acidic to alkaline seafloor settings, including conditions where only partially oxidized iron phases might exist. Their results show that alanine formation depends on having both oxidized and reduced iron present (mixed Fe(II)/Fe(III)) at alkaline pH. [22]\nThis connects directly to origin\u2011of\u2011life discussions of \u201cgreen rust\u201d\u2011like chemistry (mixed\u2011valence Fe hydroxides) and iron\u2011rich sediments/chimneys as environments with persistent redox/pH gradients. [53]\nTransition metal sulfides and vent minerals\nIn pyruvate reactivity landscape experiments, transition metal sulfides and sulfide minerals (e.g., pyrite, pyrrhotite/troilite analogs, chalcopyrite, arsenopyrite) strongly redirect reaction outcomes (reduction, thiolation, aldol reactions, and reductive amination). The key empirical point is not that any single mineral \u201ccatalyzes alanine,\u201d but that each mineral changes the competitive network among pyruvate sinks. [29]\nIron\u2011sulfide\u2013world proposals also emphasize FeS/Fe(OH)\u2082\u2011mediated reductive amination as a route to amino acids from \u03b1\u2011keto acids (including pyruvate \u2192 alanine), with strong metal specificity reported in the broader sulfide\u2011mineral literature. [54]\nNative metals, alloys, and meteoritic surfaces\nNative metals (Ni\u2070, Fe\u2070, Co\u2070) and meteoritic metal phases are increasingly used in vent\u2011analog experiments because they can catalyze hydrogenation and reductive amination under comparatively mild aqueous conditions. The Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) and Schlikker et al. (2024/2025, FEBS Journal) studies both place Ni\u2070 at the center of alanine synthesis from pyruvate with H\u2082/NH\u2083 in water. [55]\nCyanide reservoirs and metal\u2013cyanide complexes\nIf cyanide availability is episodic or locally sequestered, metal\u2013cyanide complexes (ferrocyanide/Prussian\u2011blue chemistry) have been proposed as storage and release vectors. Ruiz\u2011Bermejo et al. (2013, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) explicitly discuss ferrocyanides as intermediates relevant to \u03b1\u2011amino acid formation, aligning with broader \u201ccyanide\u2011first / cyanosulfidic\u201d schools. [56]\nMineral surfaces and chiral selection\nEven when synthesis is racemic, mineral surfaces can\u2014in principle\u2014bias adsorption or crystallization.\n\u2022\tRobert M. Hazen[57] et al. (2001, PNAS) report selective adsorption behavior of D\u2011 and L\u2011amino acids on calcite, with preliminary experiments indicating that D\u2011 and L\u2011alanine show selective adsorption behavior (in the same general sense as aspartic acid) on calcite surfaces. [58]\n\u2022\tHowever, mechanistic modeling suggests the energetic bias may be weak: Asthagiri & Hazen (2007, Langmuir / surface science context; accessible summary) report DFT results with <1 kcal/mol differences in adsorption energies for D\u2011 vs L\u2011alanine on a chiral calcite surface, implying only modest equilibrium selectivity unless amplified by additional processes. [59]\n\u2022\tEnantioselective adsorption and resolution on homochiral quartz has also been tested experimentally (e.g., alanine adsorption onto D\u2011 vs L\u2011quartz as a possible prebiotic mechanism). [60]\nThese surface processes are best treated as post\u2011synthetic selection/amplification modules, not primary synthetic routes.\nExperimental evidence and quantitative performance\nBenchmarks from key prebiotic simulation experiments\nSpark discharge (atmospheric) * Miller (1953, Science): \u03b1\u2011alanine detected from CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082/H\u2082O discharge system; water boiled; discharge ~1 week; yields reported qualitatively in milligram range; \u03b1\u2011 and \u03b2\u2011alanine identified. [4]\nJohnson et al. (2008, Science): alanine abundance relative to glycine ranges from 2.7\u00d710\u207b\u00b2 up to ~0.9\u20131.4 depending on apparatus configuration (Table S1); glycine yields (as % of methane carbon) reported in supporting text as 2.1%, 1.8%, 0.4% for three apparatus runs, allowing approximate alanine yield estimation by scaling with molar ratios. [45]\n Parker et al. (2011, PNAS): H\u2082S/CH\u2084/NH\u2083/CO\u2082 discharge produced 23 amino acids; alanine among abundant chiral amino acids reported racemic within \u00b110% (D/L ~1). [10]\nIron oxyhydroxide gradients (hydrothermal sediment/chimney analog) * Barge et al. (2019, PNAS): maximum ~70% alanine (with ~30% lactate) from pyruvate + ammonia at pH 10, Fe(II):Fe(III)=1:1, 70\u202f\u00b0C, with completion over 48\u201372 h; strong dependence on Fe redox state (too reduced \u2192 lactate; too oxidized \u2192 no reaction). [48]\nNative\u2011metal / meteorite catalysis (hydrothermal/vent inspired, but mild aqueous) * Kaur et al. (2024, Chem): pyruvate (30 mM) + NH\u2083, pH 7\u20138, 22\u202f\u00b0C, 24 h, H\u2082 5 bar, yields ~17% alanine over Ni nanoparticles and ~44% over Pd nanoparticles (in the cited comparison). [26]\nSchlikker et al. (2024/2025, FEBS Journal): pyruvate \u2192 alanine over Ni\u2070 at pH 11, 80\u202f\u00b0C, H\u2082 5 bar, 18 h: 7.6% conversion without pyridoxal vs 34% conversion with pyridoxal; higher\u2011temperature cases up to ~48% conversion reported. Also demonstrates pyridoxal \u2192 pyridoxamine formation at ~5 mM NH\u2083 and H\u2082 5 bar on Ni\u2070 at pH 11. [34]\n Novikov & Copley (2013, PNAS): pyruvate + NH\u2084Cl (70 mM) in vent\u2011gas mixtures (H\u2082/H\u2082S/CO\u2082) at 25\u2013110\u202f\u00b0C produces alanine in the presence of multiple sulfide minerals, but \u201cat strikingly different levels,\u201d emphasizing mineral\u2011dependent pathway pruning. [29]\nAminonitrile\u2011first / Strecker\u2011adjacent * Diederich et al. (2023, PNAS): in their alkaline cyanide/ammonium condition, alanine reported at 180 \u00b5M and 0.02% yield (basis NH\u2084Cl) after 7 days, linking acetaldehyde availability to observed alanine formation. [16]\nGreen et al. (2023, JACS): acetaldehyde\u2011skeleton aminonitrile and N\u2011formylaminonitrile formation can be driven to high conversion in formamide systems with staged heating, supporting a plausible \u201cprecursor pool\u201d* for later alanine release by hydrolysis. [14]\nL\u2011alanine specifically: what is actually demonstrated?\nAcross essentially all direct synthesis experiments listed above, alanine is produced as DL (racemic) unless chiral selection is built in. This is explicit for the sulfur\u2011rich discharge experiments (alanine racemic within measurement error). [61]\nThus, \u201cprebiotic synthesis of L\u2011alanine\u201d is best supported empirically as: 1) robust synthesis of \u03b1\u2011alanine (DL) under multiple plausible geochemical regimes, and 2) plausible routes to small alanine enantiomeric excess (either photochemical or surface\u2011selective), which then require amplification to approach homochirality.\nEnvironmental context and plausibility\nAlkaline hydrothermal vents and serpentinizing systems\nIf alanine is targeted as part of a protometabolic network, serpentinizing hydrothermal settings are unusually compatible with the pyruvate \u2192 alanine axis because they can supply:\n\u2022\tH\u2082 as reductant (from serpentinization),\n\u2022\thigh pH effluents (often pH 9\u201311; hyperalkaline systems even higher),\n\u2022\tmineral catalysts including iron phases and, in some models/locations, native metals or metal alloys.\nBarge et al. explicitly frame their iron oxyhydroxide chemistry as representative of early\u2011Earth seafloor sediments/vent settings with gradients, and their best alanine yields occur at warm temperatures consistent with vent\u2013ocean interface regions rather than black\u2011smoker extremes. [22]\nSchlikker et al. explicitly map their Ni\u2070/pyridoxal chemistry to serpentinization\u2011like conditions (pH 11, 80\u202f\u00b0C; H\u2082 5 bar), arguing that such systems can support both mineral\u2011tethered amino synthesis and a transition to soluble cofactor\u2011mediated amino transfer. [34]\nVolcanic plumes, lightning, and post\u2011rainout aqueous processing\nDischarge experiments most naturally map onto localized reducing environments (e.g., volcanic plumes) even if the global atmosphere is less reducing. The Parker et al. analysis argues that H\u2082S\u2011rich volcanic plume chemistry can generate amino acids in distributions similar to some meteorite amino\u2011acid patterns, and that products could accumulate in tidal regions after rainout for further processing. [10]\nThis setting is particularly relevant if the aim is to produce HCN and aldehydes (feedstocks for Strecker chemistry) rather than relying on sustained global cyanide inventories. [62]\nEvaporitic pools, wet\u2013dry cycling, and cyanosulfidic networks\nStrecker chemistry and aminonitrile stabilization routes often benefit from: * concentration by evaporation/freezing, * intermittent pH shifts, * UV\u2011driven redox chemistry and sulfide photochemistry.\nThe \u201ccyanosulfidic chemistry\u201d program (e.g., Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry) is widely discussed as a surface\u2011environment network producing precursors for nucleotides, amino acids, and lipids from shared feedstocks (HCN\u2011derived chemistry plus sulfur photoredox), and it provides a conceptual home for alanine precursors (aminonitriles) even when free alanine is not the dominant primary product. [63]\nExtraterrestrial synthesis and delivery plus parent\u2011body processing\nUV processing of interstellar ice analogs yields amino acids including alanine in complex residues (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002, Nature), providing a credible extraterrestrial source term. [38]\nHowever, for L\u2011alanine, meteoritic evidence is mixed. Cronin & Pizzarello\u2019s review (1999, Advances in Space Research) notes that a previously reported substantial L\u2011alanine excess was not observed in carefully fractionated extracts, suggesting that strong alanine enantiomeric excess in meteorites is not robust compared with \u03b1\u2011methyl amino acids (e.g., isovaline) where L\u2011excesses are more consistently discussed. [64]\nOpen questions and challenges\nThe central bottleneck: homochirality for alanine\nMost synthesis routes yield DL\u2011alanine, and even when small ee can be induced (e.g., circularly polarized UV producing up to ~4% optical purity in alanine films), that signal must be amplified by additional processes to reach biologically relevant homochirality. [65]\nMineral surface selectivity is plausible but may be weak for alanine specifically: calcite adsorption experiments suggest selectivity exists in principle, but DFT indicates adsorption energy differences can be <1 kcal/mol\u2014implying that strong ee likely requires repeated cycling, amplification, or coupling to crystallization dynamics rather than single\u2011pass adsorption. [66]\nFeedstock realism: cyanide and ammonia availability\nAlanine\u2019s Strecker route is chemically efficient in the lab but depends on: * sufficiently available CN\u207b/HCN (possibly episodic, localized, or stored in complexes), * NH\u2083 availability and pH regimes that allow imine formation and subsequent steps.\nFerrocyanide reservoir proposals address cyanide storage but add geochemical requirements (iron availability, redox conditions, UV/thermal release pathways). [56]\nFor vent pathways, NH\u2083 generation and concentration remain under active debate; recent serpentinization\u2011inspired experiments often assume millimolar NH\u2084\u207a/NH\u2083 is available, while some models suggest only lower background levels. The Schlikker study is notable for showing effects down to ~5 mM NH\u2083 in a Ni\u2070/pyridoxal framework, but extending this to sub\u2011mM regimes remains a critical challenge. [67]\nSelectivity vs. side reactions in pyruvate chemistry\nAcross mineral and metal systems, pyruvate\u2019s dominant competitor pathway is reduction to lactate. Barge et al. demonstrate that controlling redox state of iron precipitates can shift selectivity strongly to alanine (up to ~70%), while Schlikker et al. show pyridoxal can suppress lactate formation on Ni\u2070. These are strong levers, but both rely on maintaining specific redox/pH regimes. [68]\nThe Novikov & Copley landscape framing underscores a broader issue: different minerals \u201cprune\u201d the network into different dominant products; hence, scaling a single\u2011mineral laboratory result to a heterogeneous vent wall requires mixed\u2011mineral tests and transport/compartment models. [29]\nIntegration: getting from precursors to persistent pools\nFor Strecker/aminonitrile routes, the central integration challenge is coupling: * precursor formation (aldehydes/HCN/aminonitriles) to * hydrolysis / release of free amino acids without losing material to irreversible polymerization or dilution.\nFormamide\u2011rich \u201cprotected nitrile\u201d chemistry (Green et al.) provides one plausible stabilization path, but it shifts the burden to geochemical plausibility of sustained formamide\u2011rich microenvironments and to downstream hydrolysis conditions. [46]\nA plausible synthesis-network design inference\nPutting the quantitative literature together suggests a pragmatic network design strategy (inference from multiple experiments):\n\u2022\tIf the environment supplies H\u2082 and alkaline pH, pyruvate\u2011based reductive amination on Fe/Ni phases can yield alanine at tens of percent to ~70% in days or less, making it a high\u2011yield \u201ccore module.\u201d [69]\n\u2022\tIf cyanide chemistry is available (episodically or via reservoirs), Strecker/aminonitrile routes offer an independent \u201csurface module,\u201d but may primarily populate alanine precursors unless hydrolysis is explicitly enabled. [46]\n\u2022\tEnantioenrichment of alanine likely requires a separate physical module (CPL photolysis, surface adsorption, or crystallization\u2011based amplification), because the core synthesis chemistries are not intrinsically asymmetric. [70]\n \n[1] [11] [16] [27] [40] [41] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9947100/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9947100/\n[2] [10] [61] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3078417/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3078417/\n[3] [13] [23] [25] [34] [35] [43] [67] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7617359/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7617359/\n[4] [7] [57] [62] https://labs.bio.unc.edu/goldstein/miller1953.pdf\nhttps://labs.bio.unc.edu/goldstein/miller1953.pdf\n[5] [51] https://ntrs.nasa.gov/citations/20040172574\nhttps://ntrs.nasa.gov/citations/20040172574\n[6] [8] [37] [45] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Johnsonetal2008.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Johnsonetal2008.pdf\n[9] [12] [14] [28] [44] [46] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10197134/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10197134/\n[15] [29] [50] https://www.researchgate.net/publication/250924457_Reactivity_landscape_of_pyruvate_under_simulated_hydrothermal_vent_conditions\nhttps://www.researchgate.net/publication/250924457_Reactivity_landscape_of_pyruvate_under_simulated_hydrothermal_vent_conditions\n[17] [21] [32] [63] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4568310/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4568310/\n[18] [19] [56] https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11084-013-9336-3\nhttps://link.springer.com/article/1